Either way, many people seem excited, ready to “invest”, and time is running short on the Question.

Looking at the entire crypto market cap on CMC in log-scale, there is a clear upward trend. This "natural growth rate" in a totally nascent technology industry is however punctuated with two rapid peaks (Jan-2014 and Jan-2018). My thinking in 2022 is we will see a continuation of organic (and volatile) growth at a minimum. With the more likely outcome being accelerated growth patterns coming from increasing adoption, converging technologies, maturing business models (due to increasing input from financial & regulatory bodies) and the eternal profit motive (retail and institutional investors). Caveat: opaque monetary policy (I'm looking at you Fed and SEC!) may crater the crypto market in the short term.

EU-wide holistic regulation will not see light of day by mid-August [1], and numerous other large movers have signalled they are not keen on being leaders [2]. On the other end, there is little chance of China pulling back its ban, as it seeks to promote both digi-yuan and tone down chaos in domestic financial markets. The biggest regulatory unknown in this timeframe is the U.S. from what I gather. While the trend seems to indicate a slow growth pattern for 2022, the possibility of a complete market crash seems greater than another market cap doubling in less than a year. The likeliest cause for the latter at this stage is large institutional backing, which seems unlikely as long as regulation is in the air.

Looking at historical data from https://coinmarketcap.com/charts/, there is (i) an overall growth pattern, especially recently, (ii) big fluctuations, and (ii) a precedent for an extended period of stagnation after following a crash. A crash from ~$3T or more to less than $2T or $1T seems very unlikely to me. It has happened before, after the crash in 2018 but the market seems to be more mature these days. There are more legitimate people and companies involved both in terms of producers of cryptocurrencies, infrastructure, and investors. (Yes, you still have silly things like Doge/Shiba but these account for ~2% of the market cap we are discussing here.) I can imagine the market cap growing to over $5T at some point in the next year so assigning probabilities to between $3T and $4T, $4T and $5T, and over $5T depends on when in the next year this is likely to happen and whether or not it coincides with August the 12th, or if August the 12th follows a crash. How much will the market cap grow? On one hand, I assume that central banks will not be printing as many new units of fiat currencies as they did earlier in the pandemic, which played a part in the market growth over the last year. On the other hand, some serious growth could still happen because of greater awareness and perceived legitimacy (or greater tolerance to YOLO betting from WSB), as well as wider adoption from investing platforms (Robinhood, etc...), institutional investors, and companies adopting some kind of cryptocurrency related technology (NFTs, ...). This may also help the stability of the market but it's hard to tell since things like NFTs seem pretty silly as well, despite their adoption by major businesses'. In terms of timing, August is usually an ok month for the market cap, although it isn't necessarily the best historically.
